explanation.body: Disclaimer: The explanation video for this question mistakenly refers to current as “impedance” several times. All of the written formulas in the video are still correct.

Because this is a saw tooth function, in addition to the method explained in the video, it is also possible to find the answer by dividing the peak voltage, 4 V, by \(\sqrt{3}\).

For reference, here is a table displaying average and RMS voltage values for several waveform types.

\(\begin{matrix}
\text{Function Type} & V_{Average} & V_{RMS} \\
\\
\text{Square} & V_{peak} & V_{peak} \\
\text{Sine} & \frac{2V_{peak}}{\pi} & \frac{V_{peak}}{\sqrt2} \\
\text{Triangle or Saw Tooth} & \frac{V_{peak}}{2} & \frac{V_{peak}}{\sqrt3}
\end{matrix}\)

Questions # 16 and 17 both refer to the same small-signal linear amplification circuit. Before the solution for problem # 16, the form of a small-signal amplifier is discussed. If you would prefer to skip the explanation of small-signal amplifiers and the solution for problem # 16, the solution for problem # 17 begins at 1:26:22.
